<exercises xml:id="quick-practice-rates" class="unnumbered">
<title>Quick practice</title>

<exercise><statement> <p> What is a rate that you are familiar or
comfortable
with, and thinking of that rate as the slope between two points on a
graph, what measurements would the corresponding axes on that graph
represent?</p> </statement>
<solution><p> Most of what I understand in physics is limited to the
fact that velocity describes the change in position relative to the
change in time. This means the vertical axis on the corresponding graph
would be <sq>position</sq> and the horizontal axis would be
<sq>time</sq>.</p>
</solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><statement> <p> The height of a plant at two time points is
given by the
values <m>h(2) = 3.4</m> and <m>h(8) = 6.9</m> what is the average rate
of change in height over the interval? Height is in centimeters and time
is in weeks.</p> </statement>
<solution><p> The height of a plant at two time points is given by the
values <m>h(2) = 3.4</m> and <m>h(8) = 6.9</m>, the average rate of
change in height over the interval is <me>\dfrac{\Delta h}{\Delta t} =
\dfrac{6.9 - 3.4}{8-2} \approx
0.583~\dfrac{\text{cm}}{\text{wk}}</me></p>
</solution>
</exercise>

</exercises>
